ding in dev builds distorts the very behavior being debugged. Suggested change: Phase B item — recording is opt-in at runtime (disabled ⇒ zero clones, not "clone and drop"), with a measured per-transaction overhead budget and a benchmark gate. [...] **15. [Consider — Phase E] Residual privacy risk in shareable mode.** Even fully pseudonymized, interest-set sizes, per-relay subscription counts, and transaction timing fingerprint a user (follow count is basically recoverable). Note the residual risk in shareable-mode docs; consider bucketing counts in shareable exports. \n  \n **16. [Consider — Phase E] Ring buffer needs a byte bound, not just a count.** One teardown-cascade transaction can be enormous (the trace carries every command, frame, and audit entry). Bound by bytes and count. [...] Assistant: Finding 1 confirmed: `redact_trace` covers `resource_commands`, `resource_coalescences`, and `invariant_results` — the `audit_log` is untouched. Checking the audit event and versioning claims: [...] 1. **Trellis's redaction hook leaks resource keys.** `redact_trace` covers resource commands, coalescences, and invariant names — but the audit log is cloned into every trace un-redacted, and `AuditEvent::ResourceOpenCoalesced` carries a full `ResourceKey`. A "shareable" capsule built on those hooks would ship the very keys you thought you'd scrubbed. Filed as [trellis#161](https://github.com/pablof7z/trellis/issues/161), now a hard gate for Phase E. \n 2. **"Replay from capsule alone" was conflating two different things.** Traces are payload-free records — you can *scrub/reconstruct* from them, but you cannot *re-execute*. Re-execution would need payload-bearing scripts (follow lists, filters) plus identical graph topology per version — a much bigger privacy surface. The epic now pins capsule v1 to scrub-only and marks re-execution an explicit non-goal. \n  \n **Other findings that changed the epic:** capsules need a **symbolication manifest** (traces are keyed by opaque NodeIds — unreadable to anyone who didn't see the session without an embedded label registry); Trellis trace versioning is exact-match-only, so the capsule needs its own **envelope version + compat policy** or every capsule attached to an old issue dies on the first format bump; the Phase D **transport decision moved into Phase A** because the lint-exemption wording depends on it; free-form reason strings became **structured reason codes** (type lints can't catch a Debug-formatted `ResourcePlan` leaking into a string); the receipt shape gained the fields its own examples required (owner-count *transition*, outcome status, parent scope, timestamps); my "agent answers why-is-my-feed-empty" exit criterion was rightly called untestable and is now a **seeded failure-scenario corpus** against a local relay fixture — deliberately including the "subscription fine, zero events came back" case, which receipts alone can't answer; and the **headless NMP host runner** is now itemized as its own (probably largest) Phase C work item. \n  \n Everything is folded into [epic #2858](https://github.com/pablof7z/nostr-multi-platform/issues/2858) with a comment documenting the review pass, and the fabric room #xray-epic-review has the outcome logged in case @fable shows up for a second pass. The reviewer's verdict on the overall plan: phase ordering is right (ADR gate → receipts → CLI → pane → capsules); the weakness was concentrated in Phase E leaning harder on the trace foundation than the code supports — which is exactly what's now fixed in the text.
