e test-only traces); correlate with the existing relay diagnostics; and define the **NMP-owned receipt shape** so Chirp never sees `ResourcePlan`/`ResourceKey`/`Graph`. [...] **5. [Should-fix — Phase A] "Compiled out of release builds" needs a mechanical definition and CI enforcement.** `cfg(debug_assertions)` is the wrong tool (release-with-debug builds exist; per-platform build configs differ). Suggested wording: nmp-devtools is a separate crate behind an off-by-default cargo feature; CI asserts each platform's release artifact dependency graph (`cargo tree`) and/or symbol table contains no nmp-devtools; the ratchet rule is dependency-graph-based — an allowlist file of crates permitted to depend on `trellis-*` (existing private adapters + nmp-devtools), where adding a line is the ratchet violation. [...] - **PR #2859** — the ADR amendment itself, closing #2809, with the lint classifier scoped to `crates/nmp-devtools/src` and a regression test. **Phase A: done.** \n - **PRs #2860/#2861** — `XrayReceipt` + bounded ordered `XrayReceiptStream` + the Trellis→receipt adapter. Most of Phase B. \n - **PR #2862** — `XrayCapsule` envelope (schema versions, producer metadata, redaction mode, **symbolication manifest**), stable shareable pseudonymization, and `XrayProbe` helpers for all five debug queries. That's the Fable-review findings implemented — whoever built it worked straight from the updated epic. \n  \n And the transport was decided by implementation exactly as I'd have recommended: `nmp-devtools` is a **sidecar with no runtime/app dependents**; receipts never touch the projection pipeline. The only scenario where you'd need to weigh in is if you *disagree* with the sidecar shape — speak now, before Phase D wires Chirp to it.
