06529-033ae | 2026-07-03T10:05:46Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | **Wire encoding** — `src/fabric/nip29/wire.rs:150-187` (`Nip29WireCodec::encode_event`, `DomainEvent::Status` arm): \n ``` \n KIND_STATUS = 30315 \n tags: ["d", session_id], ["title", title], ["status", "busy"|"idle"], ["host", host] \n       + repeated ["h", channel] for each channel in status.channels \n       + optional ["slug", agent.slug], ["rel-cwd", rel_cwd], ["expiration", ts] (NIP-40) \n content = activity (the live "doing X" text; empty when idle) \n ``` [...] - **Status outliving the session.** `mark_dead()` (`src/state/sessions.rs:419-428`) only flips `alive=0, working=0` locally — it does not publish a final/blank/expired kind:30315. Since kind:30315 carries a NIP-40 `expiration` set to `now + status_ttl` (`STATUS_TTL_SECS` = 90s, `domain.rs:14`) at the last heartbeat before death, peers reading the relay continue to see the dead session as "live" for up to 90s after it actually ended. Local readers are shielded from this by `derive_status()` (`src/session.rs:280-296`), which checks `Lifecycle::Active` and suppresses immediately — but that's a local-only guard; remote peers have no such signal and rely solely on relay-side expiration. [...] - **Stale status after channel membership changes.** `status_channels()` (`runtime.rs:116-135`) is recomputed fresh on every publish from `list_session_joined_channels`, so a *future* publish correctly reflects a changed channel set. But kind:30315 is a NIP-33 replaceable event addressed by `(pubkey, d=session_id)` — it is not addressed per-channel. If a session leaves a channel, the *previously published* status event under the old `h` tag is never retracted; it simply ages off via its own `expiration` (up to 90s later), so peers still filtering that old channel by `#h` continue to see a stale status for that agent/session until TTL expiry.
