06529-05f9c | 2026-07-03T10:27:28Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | Two audit layers exist, purpose-built for exactly this question: \n  \n 1. **`turn_start_audit()` / `turn_check_audit()`** (`src/turn_context/audit.rs:6,45`) — build a structured JSON describing cursors before/after, `joined_channels`, `evaluated.ambient_chat`, and `evaluated.awareness` (candidate channels, raw `Status` rows including `busy`/`activity`/`title`/`last_seen`/`updated_at`/`expiration` — `status_json` at `audit.rs:212-224`), plus the exact `output.text` that was emitted. Returned alongside `context` from the `turn_start`/`turn_check` RPCs (`src/daemon/server/turns.rs:112-122, 153-165`). \n 2. **`HookCallLog`** (`src/cli/hooks/hook_forensics.rs:10`) — every hook invocation appends JSONL to `<edge_home>/sessions/<session_id>/hook-calls.jsonl` (or `TENEX_EDGE_HOOK_CALL_LOG` override), recording raw stdin, process/parent-chain snapshot, redacted env, and via `context_audit()` (`hook_forensics.rs:67-97`) both the audit JSON above *and* a verbatim `context-injection` note with the exact injected text. \n  \n So: **yes**, you can answer "why is @codex working" by pulling that session's `hook-calls.jsonl`, finding the `context-audit` note, and reading `audit.evaluated.awareness.status_rows_updated_after_since` for @codex's raw `busy`/`activity`/`updated_at`/`expiration`. And you can answer "why is #xray-epic-review not-joined" by cross-referencing `joined_channels` in the audit against `list_channels()`. \n  \n **Caveat — the audit is an approximation, not an exact mirror of `build_view`'s inputs.** `awareness_json()` (`audit.rs:108-146`) only considers `candidate_channels = [rec.channel_h] + direct subchannels of rec.channel_h`, while the actual renderer's channel set (`build.rs:85-99`, `channels_for`) is `store.list_session_joined_channels(session_id)` — potentially a different/larger set (e.g., sibling task channels joined via `channels switch`). It also filters status rows by