06529-f6623 | 2026-07-04T17:59:41Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | To make Trellis lead, add one missing layer: an **authority frontier**. Every surface should be explicitly classified as: \n  \n `imperative → shadow → advisory → authoritative → projection-owned` \n  \n Right now tenex-edge has some genuinely authoritative Trellis surfaces, some Trellis-derived-but-ephemeral surfaces, and a large imperative core still deciding important state. \n  [...]  \n I fully adopt the critique's central move: the organizing structure is not "probe verbs," it is a **classification every surface carries in code**, ratcheted in CI. Five modes: \n  \n ``` \n imperative → shadow → advisory → authoritative → projection-owned \n ``` \n  \n - **imperative** — host decides and acts; no graph. \n - **shadow** — graph computes a plan *beside* the host path; plans compared, host still authoritative (Trellis's own `SHADOW_MODE.md` pattern; the zero-risk adoption lever). \n - **advisory** — graph derives the value the host emits, but the graph is **not live/long-lived** (recomputed and discarded). \n - **authoritative** — a single long-lived daemon-held graph is the one decider; every writer routes through its seam; oracle + replay + bypass-ratchet all green. \n - **projection-owned** — graph additionally leads a **DB projection** as a summarized output-frame intent (bounded by F4). \n  \n Registered in code, not prose — this is the critique's `SurfaceRegistration`, which I adopt verbatim in spirit: \n  \n ```rust \n // src/reconcile/frontier.rs  (new, code-owned; the single source of truth) \n enum SurfaceMode { Imperative, Shadow, Advisory, Authoritative, ProjectionOwned } \n struct SurfaceRegistration { \n     name: &'static str,            // "status", "subscriptions", "hook_context", ... \n     mode: SurfaceMode, \n     facts: &'static [&'static str],        // InputFact variants that feed it \n     trellis_inputs: &'static [&'static str], \n     host_effects: &'static [&'static str], // the effect sites it owns \n     bypass_risks: &'static [&'static str], // known direct-writer seams to ratchet \n } \n ``` [...] **F4 — "projection frames" exist as an idiom but "Trellis leads DB state" is a partial overreach.** Output frames (Baseline/Delta/Clear/Rebaseline) are the materialized-output channel; hook_context already uses `materialized_output` (`hook_context/mod.rs:264`). A projection frame carrying a *small intent* payload needs no new frame kind. But two hard limits bite: the charter's **keep-bulk-payloads-out** rule + the per-commit `graph.clone()` cost (F1), and **#121: one output payload type per graph** (`CHARTER.md:108`). So Trellis can lead DB *projections* only as summarized intents, and a single graph cannot emit many distinct row-type projections. This is why §2 keeps `projection` a *bounded* frontier mode, not the destination for all of tenex-edge's store. \n  [...] **Where I refine the critique:** it lists `projection-owned` as the top of the ladder and Phase 4 aims several surfaces at it. Per F4, `projection-owned` is a *constrained* summit, not the default destination. Most surfaces should stop at `authoritative`; `projection-owned` is justified only where the DB row is small, single-typed, and its drift is a real bug class (the session row's `working`/`turn_started_at` is the one strong candidate). I make that explicit in the registration so nobody promotes a bulk table into the graph and pays the clone cost for it. \n 
