06529-4b252 | 2026-07-04T17:59:41Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | ### 6. Add a CI bypass ratchet \n  \n `probe seams` should have a CI companion: \n  \n ```text \n cargo test seam_registry_has_no_unregistered_effect_writers \n cargo test no_direct_status_publish_outside_status_seam \n cargo test no_direct_subscribe_unsubscribe_outside_subscription_executor \n cargo test no_direct_set_working_outside_declared_lifecycle_seam \n ``` \n  \n This does not need perfect static analysis. Start with a ratchet: \n  \n * grep/AST check for known forbidden calls; \n * require an allowlist entry with surface/mode/reason; \n * fail when new direct effect paths appear. \n  \n The adoption docs already say parallel direct writers are forbidden after promotion.  Enforce that mechanically. \n  [...] ### 4.5 `probe seams` + CI bypass ratchet (adopt fully) \n  \n `probe seams` renders §2's table (static registration + live commit-ledger counters). The teeth are CI tests generated from the registration allowlist: \n `no_direct_status_publish_outside_status_seam`, `no_direct_subscribe_unsubscribe_outside_subscription_executor`, `no_direct_set_working_outside_declared_lifecycle_seam`. Start as grep/AST ratchet + allowlist (the same mechanism NMP uses to ratchet `trellis-*` dependents). A new direct-effect path fails the build. **This is how the safety invariant (§1) is enforced structurally** — promotion to `authoritative` is *defined* as "the ratchet for this surface is green." \n 
06529-d2108 | 2026-07-04T17:59:57Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | **Decision: a CLI verb family (`tenex-edge probe <verb>`) with `--json` as a first-class contract, backed by a daemon-resident probe engine, plus trace export into the existing Flight Recorder HTML workstation for human deep-dives. No new ratatui workstation. No new dashboard.** \n  \n Reasoning, from the actual constraints: \n  \n 1. **The daemon owns everything that matters.** The SQLite store is daemon-only (that's why `explain` is already an RPC — `src/explain.rs:3-5`), and the three live graphs sit behind `Mutex<StatusReconciler>` etc. in `DaemonState`, driven at seams like `status_seam::drive`. Any live-graph query, oracle run, or metrics counter **must** execute in the daemon. So the real product is a set of new RPC methods on the existing dispatch table (`daemon/server.rs:269` — `"explain"` is already there; we add `"probe_state"`, `"probe_why"`, `"probe_oracle"`, `"probe_stats"`); the CLI verbs are thin renderers over them, exactly like `cli/explain.rs` is today. This architecture is already proven in-tree. \n  \n 2. **The primary user is an agent.** This fabric's operators are agents living in tmux sessions with hook-injected context; the Trellis charter names "legible to tooling and AI agents" as the point. Agents consume JSON over a socket superbly and TUIs not at all. A ratatui app would serve the minority user at the majority user's expense. (tenex-edge does already depend on ratatui, so a thin `probe watch` live-tail screen is a cheap Phase-3 nicety — but it is a *renderer of the same RPCs*, never the substrate.) \n  \n 3. **The human deep-dive tool already exists — don't build a second one.** The Flight Recorder workstation (trellis#160) is a full trace-replay UI: provenance, transaction timeline, phase ladder, receipt inspector, replay/raw-trace tabs. Critically, it consumes `SerializedScenario` JSON with a pinned `TRACE_FORMAT_VERSION` — verified in `crates/trellis-testing/tests/flight_recorder_fixtures.rs`, which loads the demo's own trace files. tenex-edge's job is to **export** `SerializedScenario` traces (`probe record --export-trace`), not to reimplement the viewer. This is the exact division of labor the X-Ray epic chose for NMP capsules ("feeds NMP capsules into Trellis's Flight Recorder workstation … rather than building a second scrubber"). \n  \n 4. **CLI verbs compose into CI and cron.** The wind-tunnel half (oracle soak, fuzz, replay-assert) must run unattended. `tenex-edge probe oracle --now --json | jq .ok` in a cron job or CI step is the whole integration story. A TUI or dashboard composes into nothing. \n  \n One naming decision, taken deliberately: the verb family is **`probe`**, not `trellis`. tenex-edge's persisted receipt shape is intentionally Trellis-vocabulary-free (`state/receipts.rs:1-8`), mirroring NMP's ADR-0075 boundary. The *diagnostic surface* may legally speak Trellis vocabulary in its human/JSON output (the X-Ray precedent), but the command names should describe intent (probe, why, oracle, replay), not the substrate — so the day another engine sits behind a surface, the console doesn't lie. \n  [...] ### 1. Keep `tenex-edge probe`, but make it a conformance surface \n  \n Add a hidden CLI command: \n  \n ```text \n tenex-edge probe stats --json \n tenex-edge probe oracle --now --json \n tenex-edge probe seams --json \n tenex-edge probe why <handle> --json \n tenex-edge probe record <handle|surface> --json \n tenex-edge probe replay <capsule-id> --json \n tenex-edge probe diff <capsule-id> --mutate path=value --json \n tenex-edge probe acid <handle|capsule-id> --json \n ``` \n  \n The current CLI has `explain`, `doctor`, `debug`, etc., but no `probe` command.  `probe` should be hidden at first, like `debug`, but treated as a machine contract. \n 
06529-95f37 | 2026-07-04T17:59:57Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | ### 3.4 Shadow oracle — `tenex-edge probe oracle [--now | --history]` + a daemon task \n  \n *The heart of "is Trellis correct on THIS state, not on fixtures."* All three reconcilers already expose `assert_oracle()` (e.g. `subscriptions/mod.rs:253`) wrapping core's `assert_incremental_equals_full()` (`trellis-core/src/oracle.rs`) — which rebuilds every derived node, collection, resource-owner set, and output from canonical inputs and returns a typed mismatch (`FullRecomputeResourceMismatch` names the key and both owner vectors). Today it runs only in `cargo test`. \n  \n Build: a daemon task that, every N minutes **and** on every 100th commit per surface, clones the graph under the lock, releases the lock, runs the check off-lock, and appends an `oracle_checks` ledger row: `(surface, revision, transaction_id, ok, mismatch_json, duration_us, nodes_checked, created_at)`. `probe oracle --now` forces a run over RPC; `--history` renders the ledger; `doctor` (existing RPC) gains a line: `trellis oracle: 3/3 surfaces green, last checked rev 4812, worst-case 1.8ms`. A red row is a **Trellis engine bug or an undeclared-state bug caught in production** — the single most valuable alert this console can emit, and the definitive answer to "does the oracle hold on live state." [...] ### 4.6 `probe oracle` + `probe acid` \n  \n - `probe oracle [--now|--history]`: a daemon task clones each graph under lock, runs `assert_incremental_equals_full()` (`oracle.rs`) *off*-lock, samples into the commits ledger + a summary in `doctor`. A red row is a Trellis engine bug or an undeclared-read caught on live state — the highest-value alert this surface emits. **Honest output (the critique's #4, adopted):** it must print `oracle: green / surface-correctness: NOT PROVEN / host-seam-coverage: 43% / uncovered: session_start, cursor CAS, outbox result`. Oracle-green ≠ surface-correct. \n - `probe acid <handle>`: produce the why-chain, then verify it counterfactually via preview/replay — remove each claimed cause → artifact MUST change; mutate a non-cause → artifact MUST stay byte-identical. Output `CONFIRMED (necessity + non-cause invariant)` or `FALSIFIED`. This tests *necessity of claimed causes under chosen mutations* (the critique's precise scoping — not global completeness), and it is the only instrument in the ecosystem that checks its own explanations. [...] **Renders are honest.** `render_oracle` prints `surface-correctness: NOT proven (oracle checks the graph's bookkeeping, not host effects)` plus `uncovered: turn_lifecycle, cursor, session_start, outbox`, and hook_context as "not a live graph (advisory)" — and there's a test locking that in (`oracle_render_is_honest_about_correctness`). Simulate prints "(nothing is applied)" and "NO CHANGE (deduped — no publish)"; why prints the latest-per-key footer; subscriptions-simulate returns `implemented: false` with a v2 message rather than silently missing. I found no overclaims in the output surfaces. \n 
06529-0788b | 2026-07-04T17:59:57Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | ### 3.5 Value meter — `tenex-edge probe stats [--since <ts>]` \n  \n *Is Trellis earning its keep, in numbers.* This requires new instrumentation, because the current design deliberately drops the evidence: no-op commits leave no receipt (subscriptions records only `if !effects.is_empty()`; status only when `event_ids` non-empty). Add an in-daemon counters struct (persisted periodically to a `probe_counters` table), incremented at the three drive seams: \n  \n | Counter | Question it answers | \n |---|---| \n | `status.commits`, `status.published`, `status.suppressed` (commit produced no command), split by trigger (`on_tick`/`on_turn_*`/`on_distill`/`on_channels_changed`) | **How many publishes did dedup avoid?** The old path published every ~30s heartbeat per session regardless; suppressed-tick count × old-path behavior = avoided relay writes. | \n | `status.refresh_vs_replace` | Is the NIP-40 re-arm actually distinct from content churn? | \n | `subs.opens`, `subs.closes`, `subs.coalesced_joins`, `subs.live_now`, `subs.max_live` | **Open/close balance over a long run** — the leak, quantified. `closes + live_now == opens` or something is wrong. | \n | `hook.renders`, `hook.frames_emitted`, `hook.unchanged` | **How many hook recomputes were no-ops?** (`FrameKind::Unchanged` is already computed per render, then thrown away.) | \n | `<surface>.commit_duration_us` histogram (p50/p95/max), `<surface>.node_count` | **Is the per-commit clone cost acceptable at real load?** Measured where it happens, per graph, correlated with graph size. | \n  \n Honesty requirement baked into the UX: the "vs the old 5-trigger path" comparison is a **model, not a measurement** — the old path is deleted. `probe stats` must label it: `avoided publishes (modeled vs 30s-heartbeat baseline): ~1,240/day`. A probe console that silently flatters is worse than none. [...] Store methods: `record_commit(&NewCommit)->R