06529-4cc10 | 2026-07-04T17:59:57Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | ### 3.8 Counterfactual diff — `tenex-edge probe diff <capsule> --mutate <step>.<field>=<value>` \n  \n *"What if this input had been different?"* — the interaction that is uniquely cheap because plans are data, and the one no log-based system can offer. Run two `TrellisHarness` replays of the same capsule: verbatim, and with one drive-arg mutated (a channel added to a `CoverageSnapshot`, `working=true` flipped, a presence row removed, the cursor zeroed). Diff the two scenarios step-by-step: commands emitted/suppressed, frames Baseline/Delta/Unchanged, receipt deltas — rendered as a per-step `±` table, `--json` for agents. Uses `Scenario::assert_step_resource_commands`-style comparison, inverted to *report* rather than assert. This is both a debugging tool ("would the leak have happened if the session had left cleanly?") and a value demonstration ("here is the exact minimal decision-diff for a one-fact change — try producing that from your logs"). \n  [...]  \n ### Phase 2 — counterfactual diff \n  \n Only after capsules exist: \n  \n ```text \n tenex-edge probe diff capsule:123 --mutate inputs.activity="reviewing PR" \n ``` \n  \n Output: \n  \n ```json \n { \n   "artifact_changed": true, \n   "before": { \n     "status_command_hash": "sha256:a" \n   }, \n   "after": { \n     "status_command_hash": "sha256:b" \n   }, \n   "diff": { \n     "activity": ["reading logs", "reviewing PR"] \n   } \n } \n ``` \n  \n For status, diff the `StatusCommand` or domain `Status` before signing and before expiration stamping. For subscriptions, diff desired resource keys/effects. For hook context, diff `FabricView` and rendered text. \n 
06529-dbf97 | 2026-07-04T17:59:57Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | ### 3.9 Adversarial fuzz + the legibility acid test — `probe fuzz` and `probe acid` \n  \n - **`probe fuzz --surface subs --txns 5000 --seed N`**: generate random-but-plausible drive sequences (sessions appearing/vanishing, channels joined/archived/left, interleaved ticks and distills), apply through `TrellisHarness` with the oracle after every step plus the ledger invariants (no orphan, no dup close, monotonic output revisions — all already implemented in `resource_ledger.rs`/`output_ledger.rs`). `trellis-testing` ships a `proptest` module and the repo has a `fuzz/` dir; the build is a generator of `DataTransactionScript`s, and every failure **shrinks to a replayable capsule** — a bug report that is itself a `probe replay` argument. Runs in CI nightly and as a long-run soak against a scratch daemon. \n - **`probe acid <handle>`** — the falsifier for "legibility." Given a puzzling artifact (a 30315, a hook injection, a REQ), it (1) produces the why-chain from receipts + live audit, then (2) **verifies the explanation counterfactually**: replay the surrounding capsule with the *claimed* cause-input mutated → the artifact must change; replay with a *non-cause* input mutated → the artifact must be byte-identical. Output: `explanation: CONFIRMED (necessary + non-cause invariant)` or `explanation: FALSIFIED — artifact unchanged when claimed cause removed`. This turns "why is answerable" into "why is answerable *and correct*," which is the acid the brief asks for. It is buildable precisely because 3.7 and 3.8 exist; no other system in this ecosystem can check its own explanations. \n  [...]  \n ### Phase 3 — acid test \n  \n The acid test is excellent, but it is not Phase 0. It needs deterministic capsules and stable artifact hashes. \n  \n Definition: \n  \n ```text \n For each claimed cause C: \n   remove or neutralize C \n   replay \n   artifact must change \n  \n For each selected non-cause N: \n   mutate N \n   replay \n   artifact must remain byte-identical or semantically identical \n ``` \n  \n Output: \n  \n ```json \n { \n   "result": "FALSIFIED", \n   "claim": "presence caused hook snapshot", \n   "counterfactual": "removed presence row peer-sess", \n   "expected": "artifact changes", \n   "actual": "artifact unchanged" \n } \n ``` \n  \n Important nuance: this tests **necessity** of claimed causes under chosen mutations. It does not prove the explanation is globally complete unless you also test a coverage set of non-causes. \n  [...] ### 4.6 `probe oracle` + `probe acid` \n  \n - `probe oracle [--now|--history]`: a daemon task clones each graph under lock, runs `assert_incremental_equals_full()` (`oracle.rs`) *off*-lock, samples into the commits ledger + a summary in `doctor`. A red row is a Trellis engine bug or an undeclared-read caught on live state — the highest-value alert this surface emits. **Honest output (the critique's #4, adopted):** it must print `oracle: green / surface-correctness: NOT PROVEN / host-seam-coverage: 43% / uncovered: session_start, cursor CAS, outbox result`. Oracle-green ≠ surface-correct. \n - `probe acid <handle>`: produce the why-chain, then verify it counterfactually via preview/replay — remove each claimed cause → artifact MUST change; mutate a non-cause → artifact MUST stay byte-identical. Output `CONFIRMED (necessity + non-cause invariant)` or `FALSIFIED`. This tests *necessity of claimed causes under chosen mutations* (the critique's precise scoping — not global completeness), and it is the only instrument in the ecosystem that checks its own explanations. \n 
06529-db359 | 2026-07-04T17:59:57Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | 1. **Safety invariant enforcement.** Every authoritative seam's executor is refactored so the *only* way to produce an effect is: stage facts → `preview()` → inspect the returned plan → then `commit()` and apply. The bypass ratchet (§4.5) asserts no effect call site exists outside that pattern. "No agent effect without a machine-reviewable plan first" becomes a structural property of the seam, verified by F1's guarantee that preview and commit run identical pipelines. \n 2. **`probe simulate <surface> --fact <InputFact-json>`** — stage a candidate fact, `preview()`, return the plan/frames/receipt as JSON, discard. This is "what happens if I commit this?" for agents — a Terraform-plan for a status/subscription change, answerable in-daemon in microseconds without touching the relay. \n 3. **Counterfactual diff (§4) becomes two previews**, not two full replays, when the question is about the *current* graph state: `preview(baseline_fact)` vs `preview(mutated_fact)`, diff the two `TransactionResult`s. (Full-history counterfactuals still need capsule replay; preview covers "from here.") \n 4. **Reproduce/visualize**: preview is the mechanism by which the acid test verifies a claimed cause without mutating live state — stage the "cause removed" fact, preview, assert the artifact changes. [...] **Tested (beyond the shipped unit tests):** I wrote a fresh demonstration on a **resource-owning graph modeled on tenex-edge's real use case** — a set of channels driving one relay-subscription Open/Close each — and ran it. It proved all four properties of a true dry-run: \n  \n | Step | Result | \n |---|---| \n | `preview(drop "random")` | returns `[Close(sub:random)]` — the plan a commit *would* emit | \n | graph after preview | **unchanged**: `random` still open, `Revision(1)` unchanged, input still `{general, random}` | \n | `preview(add "ops")` from the *same* state | a *different* plan `[Open(sub:ops)]`; `ops` not opened, revision still 1 — previews are independent and apply nothing | \n | `commit(drop "random")` | plan **equals** the earlier preview; `random` now actually CLOSED; revision advanced | \n  \n So `preview()` is genuinely the "what would committing this fact produce?" simulation — the plan you'd get, with zero mutation to the live graph — which is exactly what Phase 1's `probe simulate` and the safety invariant are built on. The throwaway demo and the merged worktree/branch are cleaned up. \n  [...] ## Fix 1 — the `--now` units bug \n  \n **Unit confirmed: `now` is unix SECONDS.** Evidence in `src/reconcile/status/mod.rs`: the TTL re-arm bucket is `now / self.refresh_secs` (`mutate` line 241, `on_session_started` line 152), and `to_status` computes `expires_at = now.saturating_add(self.ttl_secs)` (lines 309-313) — plain seconds arithmetic. The preview path uses the identical `n / self.refresh_secs` in `preview_stage` (`src/reconcile/status/probe.rs:93`). \n  \n **Changed** (`src/cli/probe/mod.rs`): \n - `Simulate::now` help (~line 61): was `"Wall-clock millis; when set, re-arms the TTL exactly as a real distill."` → now states unix **seconds**, explains the `now / refresh_secs` bucket, and warns that millis lands in the wrong bucket and fabricates a spurious TTL refresh. \n - `Oracle::now` help (~line 42): tightened to explicitly say it is advisory/no-op — accepted for symmetry but IGNORED (the oracle always runs live), so it no longer implies behavior it lacks. \n  \n **No hidden conversion in the simulate path** — confirmed straight-through: CLI `now: Option<u64>` → `json!({… "now": now})` → daemon `params.get("now").and_then(Value::as_u64)` → `preview_on_distill(session, title, activity, now)` → `set_input(arm, now / refresh_secs)`. The bug was purely the documented unit. \n  \n **Regression test** `now_is_unix_seconds_and_same_bucket_adds_no_spurious_refresh` (`src/daemon/server/probe/simulate.rs`): pins the unit with bucket-math assertions (seconds a few apart share a bucket; the same instant as millis maps to a *different* bucket — `assert_ne!`), then proves (1) a genuine content change with no `now` plans exactly one content `Replace`; (2) the same change with a same-bucket **seconds** `now` plans the same single `Replace` with `arm` absent from `changed_inputs` (no fabricated re-arm); (3) a pure dedup with same-bucket-seconds `now` stays an empty plan, whereas the millis misread fabricates a spurious `Refresh`.
