06529-e7806 | 2026-07-04T18:00:45Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | ## 1. The reconciled North Star for this effort \n  \n > **Make Trellis the first authority for tenex-edge's state transitions, such that any transition can be inspected, explained, reproduced, and simulated from its receipt alone — and use that as the flagship case study proving Trellis's three stories.** \n  \n The two halves of Trellis's own North Star map onto this cleanly, and they are the falsifiable spine: \n  \n - *"An agent never guesses what it did"* ← **receipts + replay** (the past is a lookup: the commits ledger, capsules, the acid test). \n - *"…and never gambles on what it will do"* ← **`tx.preview()`** (the future is a simulation: dry-run any fact before it commits; no effect without a plan having existed first). \n  \n Two falsifiable targets, adapted to tenex-edge (these are the case-study experiments, §7): \n  \n 1. **Diagnosis metric.** An off-the-shelf model, given *only* the serialized commit/trace stream around a **seeded** lifecycle bug (a subscription that fails to close; a status that republishes when it shouldn't), identifies root cause with ≥90% accuracy — versus its baseline from tenex-edge's raw `tracing` logs of the same incident. The delta is the publishable Story-3 result. \n 2. **Safety invariant.** On any surface at `authoritative` or above, **no host effect executes without a Trellis plan/frame having been produced first** — enforced structurally by the bypass ratchet (§4.5), not by convention. This is the operational form of "never gamble." \n  \n "Trellis leads + perfect reproduce + case study" is one loop, not three projects: leadership *creates* the receipts that make reproduce possible, and the reproduce/inspect instruments are exactly the conformance gates that let us promote the next surface safely — and the record of the frontier moving *is* the case study.
06529-f6a33 | 2026-07-04T18:00:45Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 |  \n The existing `receipts` table stores surface, transaction id, revision, changed summary, commands, artifact ref, and timestamp.  That is useful for `explain`, but not enough for a value meter. \n  \n You need a separate **`reconcile_commits`** or **`trellis_commits`** ledger that records every transaction, including: \n  \n * no-op commits; \n * unchanged recomputes; \n * suppressed publishes; \n * empty output frames; \n * command count by kind; \n * duration; \n * graph size; \n * oracle result; \n * trigger/fact kind; \n * surface mode; \n * whether host effects were applied. \n  \n Do not overload `receipts`. Receipts explain artifacts. Commit ledgers measure Trellis. \n  [...] ### 4.1 The all-commit ledger (adopt the critique fully) \n  \n The single most important build item, and the critique is right that it must **not** overload `receipts` — receipts explain *artifacts* (the 30315, the injection), and only exist for effectful commits (`status_seam.rs:48`, `subscriptions.rs:54`). The value/no-op question needs **every** transaction. New table: \n  \n ```sql \n -- state/trellis_commits.rs (new) \n CREATE TABLE trellis_commits ( \n   id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, \n   surface TEXT, txn_id INTEGER, revision INTEGER, \n   mode TEXT,                         -- SurfaceMode at commit time \n   trigger_kind TEXT, trigger_ref TEXT,   -- which InputFact / method drove it \n   changed_inputs_json TEXT, changed_derived_json TEXT, changed_collections_json TEXT,  -- LABELS not ids (§4.2) \n   resource_commands_json TEXT, output_frames_json TEXT, \n   command_count INTEGER, output_count INTEGER, effect_count INTEGER, suppressed_count INTEGER, \n   noop INTEGER,                      -- committed but changed nothing \n   oracle_status TEXT, oracle_error TEXT,  -- sampled (§4.3) \n   duration_us INTEGER, graph_nodes INTEGER, graph_resources INTEGER, \n   created_at INTEGER \n ); \n ``` \n  \n Written at each drive seam (add a `record_commit` sibling to `record_receipt` in `instrument.rs`). This makes `probe stats` answer the real questions the original doc's counters approximated: publishes suppressed (status commits where `command_count==0`), refresh-vs-replace split, subs open/close balance (`Σopen − Σclose == live_now`), hook renders that were `FrameKind::Unchanged` (already computed at `receipt.rs:56`, currently discarded), and the per-commit `duration_us`/`graph_nodes` histogram that answers "is the clone cost acceptable at real load" — measured where it happens. [...]  \n Trellis's promise (README, `~/src/trellis/README.md:148-164`) is that the receipt "is the product": systems built on it are *legible* — diffable, replayable, explainable to tooling and agents "without parsing logs" — and *provably honest* via `assert_incremental_equals_full()`. The shipped tenex-edge adoption (`docs/trellis-adoption.md`) claims three concrete wins: the subscription leak is dead, five status-publish triggers collapsed to one deduped path, and the hook-context receipt cannot drift from the render. Every one of those claims is currently backed by **unit tests only**. The oracle runs in `#[cfg(test)]`. Receipts persist only for commits that produced effects (`status_seam.rs:48`, `daemon/server/subscriptions.rs:54`), so the most valuable events for the value question — the *suppressed* publishes, the *no-op* recomputes — leave no trace at all. Nobody can currently answer "did Trellis earn its keep this week" from a running fabric. [...] 2. **Value meter.** The current receipts ledger does not record the most important value evidence. Status receipts are skipped when no event is published.  Subscription receipts are skipped when no open/close effect occurs.  Therefore “how much work did Trellis suppress?” cannot be answered from persisted data today. \n  [...] ### 3. Node IDs are currently insufficient evidence \n  \n `changed_summary_json` persists graph-local numeric `NodeId`s as arrays of integers. Its own comment says these are graph-local numeric ids.  A receipt saying `{"inputs":[2,3]}` is not a durable explanation. It is only useful while someone remembers how the graph was built. \n  \n Phase 0 should not merely “label receipt node ids.” It should introduce a **stable node label registry** per surface: \n  \n ```text \n status/<session>/working \n status/<session>/title \n status/<session>/activity \n status/<session>/channels \n status/<session>/ttl-arm \n subscriptions/daemon/channels \n subscriptions/daemon/addressed-pubkeys \n subscriptions/session/<session>/channels \n hook/<session>/cursor \n hook/<session>/presence \n hook/<session>/messages \n ``` \n  \n Persist both id and label: \n  \n ```json \n { \n   "inputs": [ \n     {"id": 12, "label": "status/s1/activity"} \n   ], \n   "derived": [ \n     {"id": 18, "label": "status/s1/content"} \n   ], \n   "collections": [ \n     {"id": 19, "label": "status/s1/coll"} \n   ] \n } \n ``` [...] ### 4.2 Stable node-label registry (adopt fully — Phase 0) \n  \n The shipped `changed_summary` persists graph-local integer ids (`{"inputs":[2,3]}`, `instrument.rs:112`) — useless to a human or agent a day later. Build a per-surface `NodeLabels{ by_id: BTreeMap<NodeId, String> }` populated at node creation (the reconcilers already name every node: `"activity"`, `"daemon-channels"`, `hook`'s six inputs are labeled at `hook_context/mod.rs:180-187`). Labels are stable, semantic paths: `status/<session>/activity`, `subscriptions/session/<session>/channels`, `hook/<session>/cursor`. Persist **both** id and label in the commits ledger and receipts v2. This is the precondition for every legibility claim — an agent cannot diagnose from `[2,3]`. [...] ### Step 2 — Node-label registry (`src/reconcile/labels.rs`, NEW) \n ```rust \n pub struct NodeLabels { by_id: BTreeMap<NodeId, String> }   // Default + Clone \n   fn new() \n   fn record(&mut self, id: NodeId, label: impl Into<String>)   // called AT node creation \n   fn label_of(&self, id: NodeId) -> Option<&str> \n   fn labels_for(&self, ids: &[NodeId]) -> Vec<String>          // unregistered → "node:<n>" \n   fn len(&self) / is_empty(&self) / iter() -> impl Iterator<(NodeId,&str)> \n ``` \n Re-exported as `crate::reconcile::NodeLabels`. Each reconciler now owns a `labels: NodeLabels` field, populated at node creation, exposed via **`pub fn labels(&self) -> &NodeLabels`** and **`pub fn graph_node_count(&self) -> usize`** (on all three: `StatusReconciler`, `SubscriptionReconciler`, `HookContextReconciler`). Semantic paths recorded: \n - status: `status/<id>/{working,title,activity,channels,arm,content,coll}` \n - subscriptions: `subscriptions/daemon/{channels,addressed_pubkeys,archived_channels,live_channels,subs}`, `subscriptions/session/<id>/{channels,subs}` \n - hook: `hook/<session>/{cursor,now,channel-meta,members,presence,messages,view}` (the materialized output is keyed by `OutputKey`, not `NodeId`, so it is not in the id-registry — deliberate). \n 
06529-614ee | 2026-07-04T18:00:45Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | **F1 — `tx.preview()` does not exist, and is nearly free to add.** `Transaction::new` builds `working: Graph<C>` as a full clone of the graph (`transaction.rs:38`). Every staging and recompute step runs against `self.working`. The real graph is untouched until the *very last line* of `commit()`: `std::mem::swap(self.graph, &mut self.working)` (`transaction.rs:285`). `Drop` just clears `transaction_open` (`transaction.rs:302`) — a dropped, uncommitted transaction discards the working copy cleanly. **So a dry run is: run the commit pipeline, build the `TransactionResult`, and return it *without the swap*.** The clone is already paid. There is no `preview`/`dry_run` in the tree today (grep-confirmed). This is real, small, and the keystone the first design missed — it is upstream ask #1. \n  [...] ```rust \n impl<'graph, C: Clone + PartialEq> Transaction<'graph, C> { \n     /// Runs the full commit pipeline on the working copy and returns the \n     /// TransactionResult WITHOUT writing back to the graph. The transaction is \n     /// consumed; the real graph is untouched. Nearly free — the working clone \n     /// is already paid at `begin_transaction`. \n     pub fn preview(mut self) -> GraphResult<TransactionResult<C>>; \n } \n ``` \n  \n Implementation is `commit()` minus the final `std::mem::swap` and minus mutating the *real* graph's audit state (record audit onto `working` so the returned result carries explanations, then drop `working`). ~30 lines, reusing the existing pipeline. I will draft this PR against `~/src/trellis` and its test (`preview_does_not_mutate_graph`, `preview_result_equals_commit_result_then_discard`) as the opening move — it is the cleanest possible "tenex-edge feeds Trellis" artifact. [...] **Tested (beyond the shipped unit tests):** I wrote a fresh demonstration on a **resource-owning graph modeled on tenex-edge's real use case** — a set of channels driving one relay-subscription Open/Close each — and ran it. It proved all four properties of a true dry-run: \n  \n | Step | Result | \n |---|---| \n | `preview(drop "random")` | returns `[Close(sub:random)]` — the plan a commit *would* emit | \n | graph after preview | **unchanged**: `random` still open, `Revision(1)` unchanged, input still `{general, random}` | \n | `preview(add "ops")` from the *same* state | a *different* plan `[Open(sub:ops)]`; `ops` not opened, revision still 1 — previews are independent and apply nothing | \n | `commit(drop "random")` | plan **equals** the earlier preview; `random` now actually CLOSED; revision advanced | \n  \n So `preview()` is genuinely the "what would committing this fact produce?" simulation — the plan you'd get, with zero mutation to the live graph — which is exactly what Phase 1's `probe simulate` and the safety invariant are built on. The throwaway demo and the merged worktree/branch are cleaned up. \n  \n The keystone is now real and landed upstream. Phase 1 slice [#233](https://github.com/pablof7z/tenex-edge/issues/233) (wire `tx.preview()` → `probe simulate`) is unblocked whenever you want to start building the frontier program.
06529-ee5c4 | 2026-07-04T18:00:45Z | session:065295ad-311d-4965-a3c1-6f749135f2b8 | - **The oracle and the inspector cost clones on a live daemon.** Every commit already snapshots the graph (Trellis's stated deal: cost scales with graph size, not change size — README "performance deal"), and `full_recompute_check` clones *again*. Today's graphs are small (hook: 8 nodes; status/subs: O(sessions + channels)), so single-digit-ms is likely — but the lock is the shared reconciler lock. Mitigation is designed in (clone under lock, check off-lock; commit-count sampling, not every-commit), and `probe stats`' duration histograms are themselves the regression alarm. If p95 commit time grows past ~10ms at real load, that is a *finding about Trellis*, and the console must report it as one, not tune it away. \n - **The oracle cannot see the host-side shadow state.** `StatusReconciler.last`, `last_view`, the `sessions` maps, and every effect translator (`to_effects`, `translate`) sit outside the graph. A green oracle proves the *graph's* bookkeeping, not that `translate` built the right expiring publish. The seam map (3.6) names these; replay ledgers (3.7) partially cover them; but "oracle green" must never be rendered as "surface correct" — the UX should print exactly what was checked (the `FullRecomputeCheck` lists are returned for this reason). \n - **Retrospective coverage is effectful-commits-only, and three surfaces only.** Suppressed publishes get counters (Phase 0) but still no per-event receipts — you can count no-ops, not *explain a specific one* after the fact (the live `probe why` covers the recent case; a sampled no-op receipt mode is a possible Phase-3 add). And `rpc_session_start`, the outbox drainer, tmux, profile warming, relay I/O, and the cross-process cursor CAS are **invisible to this console entirely**. The single biggest UX risk is false confidence: a beautiful why-chain for the 20% of the system on Trellis while the bug lives in the imperative 80%. Countermeasure: `probe seams` is a first-class verb, the map ships in Phase 1, and every "no receipts found" response names the uncovered surfaces rather than returning an empty list. [...]  \n Oracle green proves Trellis’s incremental bookkeeping equals a full recompute. It does **not** prove the host supplied the right facts, applied the right effects, signed the right event, advanced the right cursor, or wrote the right DB projection. \n  \n That caveat is not minor. The Trellis mapping explicitly keeps host observations/effects outside the graph.  Therefore the probe output must say: \n  \n ```text \n oracle: green \n surface correctness: not proven \n host seam coverage: 43% \n uncovered mutators: rpc_session_start, cursor CAS, outbox publish result, tmux pane stamp \n ``` [...]  \n - **Charter tension — clone cost vs in-graph state.** Every transaction clones the graph (F1); every promoted surface and every capsule adds state and commits. Mitigations are designed in: `projection-owned` is bounded to small single-typed rows (§2, F4); the journal-as-first-writer is only on high-value seams (§5, refining the critique's "everywhere"); the commits-ledger `duration_us`/`graph_nodes` histogram is itself the regression alarm. If p95 commit grows past ~10ms at real load, that is a *finding about Trellis to report*, not to tune away. **Where does "Trellis leads DB state" stop?** At summarized single-typed projections; bulk tables stay imperative and the seam map says so. \n - **The agent-audit story depends on explanation serialization (F2a).** Today an exported trace lets an agent see *what* recomputed and *which* commands fired (legible with labels) but not the shortest dependency path. Experiment A runs on structural causality now; the ≥90% claim may need upstream ask #2 to hit its ceiling. Don't over-promise Story 3 until that lands or the experiment shows structural causality suffices. \n - **Oracle-green ≠ surface-correct; covered 20% vs imperative 80%.** The oracle proves the *graph's* bookkeeping, not that the host supplied the right facts, signed the right event, or advanced the right cursor — and it is blind to the host-side shadow state inside the reconcilers themselves (`StatusReconciler.last`, `HookContextReconciler.last_view`, the `sessions` maps). Every `probe` output must print what was and wasn't proven and name the uncovered mutators (§4.6). The single biggest UX failure mode is a beautiful why-chain for the leading surfaces while the bug lives in imperative `session_start` — which is exactly why `probe seams` is first-class and `session_start` is deliberately held at shadow/advisory (full authority over its interleaved DB/relay/signer/spawn/tmux effects is a trap: high blast radius, low reproduce-value, charter-hostile). \n - **Capsule / receipt volume + privacy.** `llm_calls` stores verbatim transcripts forever; subscription filters carry pubkeys (X-Ray flagged interest-shape as the privacy-bearing field); capsules add drive logs. Adopt bounded retention (bytes *and* rows), end-to-end `--redact`, and gate *shareable* trace export on the known Trellis audit-log redaction leak (trellis#161) — until it lands, exported capsules are local-only. [...] - **A checked-in map** (`docs/trellis-seams.md`, generated + hand-annotated) enumerating: the three covered surfaces and their single drive seams; the *declared* exceptions from `trellis-adoption.md` (`rpc_session_start` fully imperative; the cross-process PostToolUse cursor CAS at `turns.rs:146-158`); and — the ones the adoption doc does *not* list — the **host-side shadow state inside the reconcilers themselves**: `StatusReconciler.last: BTreeMap<String, StatusCommand>` (`status/mod.rs:83`, used to synthesize expiring publishes), `HookContextReconciler.last_view`, and the `sessions` node-handle maps. These live *outside* the graph, are *invisible to the oracle*, and are exactly where split-brain can re-enter. Naming them in the map is the point. \n - **A live verb** rendering: receipts-per-surface over the window, effect sites instrumented vs total (grep-derived allowlist of `transport`/`outbox` call sites, CI-ratcheted the way NMP ratchets `trellis-*` dependents), and any surface whose graph committed but whose seam recorded nothing. `probe seams` failing in CI when someone adds a bypass path is the mechanical form of the "no split-brain" promise. [...] 3. **Seam map.** The codebase has explicit Trellis-led seams, but it also has direct host state and effect seams: `StatusReconciler.last`, hook `last_view`, `DaemonState.subscribed_projects`, session maps, signer maps, cursor CAS, outbox, tmux, and session startup. A coverage map is necessary to prevent “oracle green” from becoming false confidence. [...] - **Oracle-green ≠ surface-correct; covered 20% vs imperative 80%.** The oracle proves the *graph's* bookkeeping, not that the host supplied the right facts, signed the right event, or advanced the right cursor — and it is blind to the host-side shadow state inside the reconcilers themselves (`StatusReconciler.last`, `HookContextReconciler.last_view`, the `sessions` maps). Every `probe` output must print what was and wasn't proven and name the uncovered mutators (§4.6). The single biggest UX failure mode is a beautiful why-chain for the leading surfaces while the bug lives in imperative `session_start` — which is exactly why `probe seams` is first-class and `session_start` is deliberately held at shadow/advisory (full authority over its interleaved DB/relay/signer/spawn/tmux effects is a trap: high blast radius, low reproduce-value, charter-hostile).
